The tenant of Bakal: The cupcakes warm up, he signed a higher rent.
An imposing old man came out from the door of the customer center of the RPG company Byty of the "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of rented apartments in the Czech Republic.
He was carrying a file with three new rental contracts for three apartments: his own, his daughter’s and his son’s.
The deregulation increased the rent to these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 second class apartment 4100 crowns.
"And there is no hot water and heating works on solid fuel," the man who has the signature power shows his finger on his son's new contract.
“But I signed it anyway,” he explained in anger and half resigned.
The citizen association of apartments BytyOKD.cz who described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent" advises tenants not to sign and wait until December 7, when a notice will be published explaining the method to follow to claim.
But the man reacts to this with a gesture of the hand.
“One says this, the other says something else” by flanking the eyebrows.
The Ostrava region becomes the laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what awaits most apartments in the Czech Republic whose rents do not match the market price.
Aktualne.cz has therefore decided to visit the "laboratory" personally.
The RPG waiting room on Havirovska Street is one of four in the Ostrava region and is already full on Tuesday at 9 a.m.
Just next to the door stands a guard from a security company with a device to call customers.
A special button, “lease 2011”, is lit on the touch screen.
A single press and a paper with a number comes out of the device.
You don't have time to read your number "157" as your number is already starting to shine on the big screen under the waiting room topit.
In a fraction of a second, it’s your turn.
After a short moment, an old couple arrives to inquire about the rent, but the new rent doesn’t seem to concern the people in the waiting room.
The majority of people came to solve common problems as everywhere – requests for repairs, insurance-related events and more.
In the Ostrava region, people from more than 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have received mail with the new lease agreements in their mailboxes since about mid-November.
RPG Byty offers them rental increases of 15 to 38 percent.
The special store for new rentals has been open to the public since November 18.
“It has been working for almost a week, so it’s still being tested,” the employee behind the counter replies, after a moment of hesitation, when the client presents himself as a journalist.
The demolition and former miners’ apartments in Bakal are a very sensitive local topic.
The Vice-President of Parliament and from the Ostrava region, Lubomir Zaoralek of the Social Democrats, this quite firmly before the elections and this now fills the local newspapers.
“20 years after them, I want a new floor.”
"They didn't even change me a piece of board in the toilet, the man mentioned in the introduction relieves himself.
However, it is mostly, according to employees, retirees who come to be sure that they will receive a return on the new rental price if they sign now as promised by RPG in a special offer.
This is half the amount of the rent that will be paid to the other tenants who have signed their new contract before December 15.
But the "deregulation" checkpoint on Havirovaska Street is not really overwhelmed by questions.
"Of the 360 customers who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came for the rent," the employee said.
And yet RPG targets both on its website and in the vitrines of individual interviews on rents when needed.
If the two parties do not agree on the lease, an independent court will decide.
"It's not about threats, it's just about informing about the unique and legitimate way to act legally," RPG said on its website.
“Here nobody goes to court,” one of the RPG employees of Byty thinks, and the man in the street in front of the customer center gives her the right.
"I have 13,000 crowns in retirement and I have 5,000 crowns left to eat, I don't have enough to go to court," he said.
The employee suddenly feels uncomfortable.
“We will see.”
"Mr. Zaoralek in the media asks that no one sign and so people wait," she said.
Rental regulation ends in the Czech Republic with the beginning of 2011 and increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"And, moreover, the current rents still do not reach the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the housing fund," reminds Pavel Klimes, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, that it is precisely the negligence of the housing fund that makes the tenant angry is the main reason for the rental increase.
However, in 5 years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able with rent to invest in the apartments 4 billion, in four years from 2011 to 2014 this should be 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging on the ceiling in front of the covered chairs of the waiting room on Havirosvka Street, however, repeats some information indicated in red.
"The rental increase in 2011 is 15 percent and concerns no less than 3,1200 apartments or more than 90 percent of RPG apartments."
"And it will always be at a maximum of 7.50 Czech crowns per square meter per month," the screen says.
The 38 percent increase concerns only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In these cases, this is an increase of a really very low sum of 19.66 CZK per square meter," RPG added.
Next year, the rental will remain the same for 2,600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical but gradual increase over 4 to 8 years.
It adds other commitments: all the money from the rental increase (cf. the chart) is returned to the apartments in the form of heating savings - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the agreement on the rental increase have priority.
The kindergarten is also part of the offices included architects.
the administrative building Avriopoint of Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch. Design.
No one could have expected it to also be home to a mini kindergarten with everything you need – colorful walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October last year, children of Arch. design employees can visit.
Architectural project company Arch. Design. whose workshops produced a large number of constructions in Brno, imagined its mini business school from the first layouts of the Avriopoint building.
She employs around 90 people, mostly from childhood and cared that women architects and project managers could quickly return to work.
Along with part-time employment contracts, kindergarten is a bonus offered to its employees by the company Arch. Design. as part of its social program.
Builders and architects have the opportunity to combine taking work with caring for children.
It was the employees of Arch.Design. themselves who imagined this kindergarten and with the support of the management they were able to obtain a grant from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The school is funded by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme for Human Resources and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding appropriations (up to 2.8 million CZK), they were able to purchase equipment and devices and after two years to provide qualified personnel as well as the launch.
After the use of the funding grant (two years) the company Arch. Design. has the obligation after 3 years to operate the mini kindergarten on its own funds.
The preparation of the project took a year and it was the Economy rating company that helped make the grant application.
Child care is provided by qualified staff, all day a nurse and a nursery teacher take care of the children. children can go to kindergarten without age limit but they have more than three anspore most.
As it is a "mini kindergarten" there can only be 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more who replace each other.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use this school regardless of the hierarchical position.
Although this is individual care and education, the mini-pre-school program is comparable to that for preschool education.
Children do not only play there, but a quality education is also guaranteed - from the beginning to the preparation for school banks, English is taught.
The classroom is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also a computer that children can use.
The presence of young children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can at any time control their child and do not have the stress of a delay to go pick up the children in a school away from the parents’ workplace.
Parents use their working time in the most productive way.
It is not surprising that there is a natural relationship of loyalty between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.s is thus listed among the companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and are family-friendly and through this program strengthens HR marketing.
The bone house still fascinates after 100 years. take a look into the interiors of Gaudi.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase with a dinosaur spine and the balconies with open fish mouths.
This is the case of the Casa Battlo in Barcelona by the architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic shapes, the house has received from the locals the nickname of House in bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaics, façade reminiscent of scales and everywhere curves, these are all the things that are typical for Antoni Gaudi’s Art Nouveau.
The front facade of the house unfolds its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that remind nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation we see the geometry, rhythm and order thought with precision.
At night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brightness of the colors is reinforced.
The wrapping and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood copies in waves the window frames, the balustrades, the decorative elements of the doors, the eyeliner and the lamelles.
The house Battlo that stands in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia at number. 43, was born from the construction of a house of 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, initially insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of another entirely new but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-housing house was not thought of by Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was precisely on his project that the decorations for an apartment representative of the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the façade were born.
Other artists and creators have also worked on the facade.
The joint work on the plans for the Casa Battlo house began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi's house Casa Mila and the Guell Park in which there are other works of Gaudi.
Locals nicknamed the hot house just after its finishing because of its organic shapes "The House of Bones".
Others, given the specific mechanism of opening the windows, have called it "the house that bails".
It is said that on the top of the building there is a sword similar to that of St. George the patron of Catalonia.
Other sculpture elements of the construction contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought of the house as a unique system in its time of central heating, with typical windshields and fireplaces.
Their 45-degree inclination seems strange.
During the creation Gaudi absolutely did not comply with the construction guidelines of the time and did not allow himself to be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city the permission to build, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the finishing the city council was horrified and requested changes.
It didn’t like, for example, the members of the municipal council that the building pillars stumbled onto the public sidewalk.
There was never a change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo asked (and obtained satisfaction) the authorization to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and in the third one room and a private part of the apartment.
The floor was rented to a jewellery.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which access to an independent roof terrace.
All straight angles and straight lines were canceled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the salons and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit the private space for more intimate conversations.
The house with Gaudi's reconstruction has received in addition to new façades a non-traditional roof and two more floors.
Gaudi's play with light is also impressive, with blue and white glass tiles with which the inner courtyard is decorated and with light wells.
The two-color game gives maximum light to all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark that, on the contrary, absorbs the rays of the sun.
The house Casa Battlo, which was listed in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund, may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the famous creator's birth.
They continued the visits as they found it to be a lucrative business and expanded the scope of visits to the common areas and the loft including the roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really inexpensive and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discount.
The amount is still above the entrance price to Gaudi's other buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic towers, you need to quickly find a companion among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
