Devices to track people are increasingly in demand by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear of their child leads more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up in the beginning to search for cars can also be used to track the movement of people and help in some cases, such as the small Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a pencil box but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka moved a large number of people and they began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not espionage, but just another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," said Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, one of the tracking devices suppliers in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in a person's bag who is not aware, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
“The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons,” Pilin adds.
According to him, children should always know what the "box" is used for and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bockova points out that if the child does not want to wear such a thing on him, he will get rid of it.
"And even the smallest can show great creativity when it comes to deliberately getting rid of something when they don't want to be under control."
"Mobile phones, which can cut off like these tracking devices, have already brought parents to long expectations," says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in case of aggression is highly questionable.
"If it is a prepared abduction, the perpetrator will do everything to ensure that the child does not have electronic devices that can locate him."
“This is the phone.”
“As soon as the tracking devices are developed, they (criminals) will search for them as well because the sale will be supported by a advertising campaign.”
“In such cases, criminals will always be ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
She acknowledges, however, that such devices can help in the event of an unprepared assault by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of the company RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, claims that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an attack.
"The device can be configured so that it is in regular emission after a specified period of time."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains."
“The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and finds himself lying down without moving,” says Cech.
According to him, the so-called smart phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after formatting it with a special prologue.
The problem with current tracking systems is that it’s either a device similar to those we’re wearing depending on the size of a pencil box or to the smaller phone devices.
You can always lose them.
According to Pilina of the company Macro Weil, that’s why tests are currently being conducted to make devices that look like ordinary digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he will realize it after a while, which will give the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendulum, it will always use the same technology as for tracing cars.
It is a combination of position acquisition systems using GPS (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a mobile phone function that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
