So far I’m taking advantage of the contacts I’ve gained through the competitions.
The franchise sale of his hotel helped Lukas Pytloun for the place of winner of the Best Individual Entrepreneur contest.
The winner of the contest for Best Individual Entrepreneur last year was Lukas Pytloun, a 28-year-old entrepreneur.
His adventure towards success is like in a movie.
Lukas Pytloun loved to travel.
And abroad, he realized that in Libérec there was a lack of a quality accommodation site at a reasonable price.
From his savings on what he had earned while working abroad and with the help of a bank loan he bought a small 5 apartment building half demolished.
Knowing that he was still a third-year high school student, it was a courageous action.
“The ratio between quality and price of accommodation in our area made me want to do something,” says Lucas Pytloun.
He began renting the first reconstructed apartment to foreign workers.
He reinvested the profits in the building that he transformed into a pension with 54 beds.
Since then, his entrepreneurial action has allowed him to open in Libérec 4 pensions, two style restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of almost 300 beds of all accommodation categories.
The most comfortable of them was until recently the four-star Pytloun design hotel.
This year, there was another of the same quality.
"We just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrova U Tise where we sold our franchise concept and other candidates for the Pytloun hotel franchise appeared," the number one entrepreneur last year.
"And for the sale of the license for the operation of a large-scale hotel the victory in the Contest of the Entrepreneur of the Year has served well," adds Pytloun with appreciation.
The victory brought him more popularity and to be known in Libérec and its surroundings.
“People recognized me on the streets, often congratulated me and, I have to say, it was very pleasant,” he recalls.
He recommends participating in this competition to anyone who tries to do something.
It is not necessary to win, but every opportunity to be visible is good.
He says he still uses his contacts and knowledge that he could not have obtained otherwise.
“With those I met through the competition, I started to have regular business relationships.
According to him, the reputation linked to success also had an impact on employees.
There are about 70.
“I see in them above all the loyalty and pride of being engaged in something that has been generally recognized.”
“It’s not, and by far, the only result of my personal work, but the result of a good work of us all together.
“Only my name is pushed forward,” says Lucas Pytloun modestly.
I wish my successor a better year than the one we had at Farmet.
The euphoria of victory was quickly replaced by the effects of the crisis.
Thanks to the goal sense of the winning Farmet has the worst moments behind.
The one who came to pick up the prize at Slovansky dum for the first place in the competition for the Firm of the Year organized by Vodaphone last year is Karel Zdarsky, the owner of the company Farmet.
The jury rewarded the efforts with which he transformed a tooling workshop in Ceska Skalice into a company with a turnover of SEK 100 million.
“I can say that the award has encouraged not only me, but also my employees and increased our confidence in fighting against the competition,” said the winner of the competition last year.
At the beginning of the history of the company Farmet there was the desire to do something useful.
And so when the state offered Karel Zdrasky's father to rent the small workshop as compensation after the confiscation of property by the Communists, he did not hesitate long, refused a career in a firm where he worked at the time, and created a company with a few comrades in his father's surroundings for the manufacture of plastic baths.
Not long after they began to specialize in presses for vegetable oil.
After eighteen years, it became the largest manufacturer of automatic presses in Central Europe.
The company was known even to the non-specialized public after the success obtained at the contest through the media.
“Not only did our customers really get to know the Farmet brand better, but also foreign partners who began to realize that they were working with a company that achieved the greatest success in their home country,” says Karel Zdarsky.
But the past year did not happen in Farmet only in the euphoria of victory.
The company’s assessment was based on the financial results of 2008 and in part of 2009.
2009 was the hardest year for engineering machinery sales.
At the height of the crisis, which did not really affect citizens, companies were forced to stop their investment projects and begin to limit their purchases of new equipment and technologies.
“Of course we have not escaped this situation.”
“The turnover dropped 40 percent, and we had to limit our production and even fire,” explains Karel Zdarsky.
