At the Land Fund in Plzen, police carried out arrests during a public tender
In the building of the Land Fund in Plzen, anti-corruption police have carried out arrests in recent days.
Detectives passed the gloves to the local entrepreneur and real estate trader Lubos.
The latter sought to manipulate a public tender for the settlement of a restitution request in such a way that the proposed land was obtained by a specific candidate.
He had to pay Lubos G. half a million crowns.
"For now, I can only confirm that the police are prosecuting a person for the offence of initiation as part of a tender and public competition," said Antonie Zelena, the head of the Prosecutor's Office of Plzen, told the newspaper Pravo, knowing that it is forbidden to provide further explanations as the investigation is underway.
Police released the 46-year-old man after 24 hours.
To know how he could influence a public tender, one can only speculate given so little official information.
At a question from Pravo, Lubomira Cerna, a spokeswoman for the Land Fund, said that police officers had actually carried out an arrest in Plzen at a separate workplace during the public competition.
“It was a client and in no case an employee,” she said.
The public competition according to Cerna has as its real name "Call to propose rights for the transfer of land according to the Law on Land" and is set up when several candidates who are entitled to the right appear.
“These persons offer, as part of the appeal, a higher value of their rights to reimbursement that must be settled before the value of the land is announced.”
"According to the proposed rights, a ranking of buyers is set up and the Land Fund then transfers the land to the person who has proposed the highest rights," the spokesman of the Fund explained.
Lubos G. had, it is clear, the information concerning the persons who had signed up for the call and as he himself is also a beneficiary person because having purchased a large number of restitution rights, he had proposed to the candidates in the field not to participate in the contest.
Probably because of his withdrawal.
That would explain why he had so much money in his possession at the time of his arrest.
Lubos G. had contacts far above standards at the FdT (Fonds des Terres).
He appeared in the case of the former head of the FdT Vaclav Sankot who was prosecuted for publishing land for which the decision to set up a construction had already been issued.
Just Lubos G. had obtained, for example, land for the construction of public communications, specifically in the place where the access artery to the industrial area of Borske Pole was to be built.
Later he exchanged it with the town hall for a building in the historic center of the city whose value is far higher.
The municipality was forced to accept because otherwise it would endanger the construction by blocking the land.
Households will pay an extra one hundred crowns per month for the housing.
From January, households will have to pay a surcharge not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
Families will therefore have to draw from their wallets up to a hundred crowns a month more than now.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas almost 2 percent more expensive, in some locations you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity is expected to bring near-apartment households 100 crowns annually more than currently.
However, all suppliers have lowered electricity prices due to the sensitive development to encourage the manufacture of renewable energy, photovoltaic cells.
Gas increases moderately but of course at the time when people need it most to heat and therefore have the greatest consumption.
In addition, a hundred crowns can be added.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating differs from city to city.
It is mainly the largest municipalities that plan to raise prices.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay from January for central heating almost 50 crowns more per month, Libérec families will pay more than 1000 crowns annually.
For the inhabitants of Prague, a 9 percent increase is being prepared for water and sanitation in case the city increases infrastructure rent.
If the rents do not change, the Prague residents will pay an extra 6.8 percent.
Prices in Prague will still be some of the lowest compared to the whole country.
In North Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are increasing by 7.4 percent.
Rental prices will rise significantly, for example, in the 450 thousand apartments in rent from January, that is, at the end of the regulation.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns 2500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, has decided to increase up to 100 percent.
Those who disagree with the new rental increase will be brought to court by the company.
The regulated rent paid by people in 300,000 apartments could rise next year by 10 percent.
The Czech children are drunk with rum and fernet.Beer is no longer fashionable and acts gently.
Fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whisky are stolen from parents.
These are the drinks that most often bring those who are drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in the hospital for relapse are no exception.
This is a result of the experience of doctors who encounter cases similar to the admissions of children’s departments of hospitals.
“Beers or wines are no longer fashionable because it takes time to get drunk.”
“The trend is really to strong alcohols,” says Ludek Pelikan, head of the children’s department at the Horovice Hospital in Central Bohemia.
“When they manage to chipple a bottle to Daddy in the closet, it’s sometimes about whisky but it’s fernet and vodka that prevail.”
"Wodka has that advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and so not feel it," explains the head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, a spokeswoman for Motol Hospital, is also right.
“It’s usually rum or fernet.”
“Alcohol is now fashionable, especially in elementary schools.”
"In some cases, it was slivovice that they brought home," Jurinova added.
According to the head of department Pelikan, seeing drunk children aged thirteen to fourteen at hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice since last year, he was in Motol where he practiced for ten years precisely in paediatrics where ambulances brought completely drunk schoolchildren from the broad surroundings.
She was hospitalized four times.
"She began her career at the age of twelve when she was brought with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in the blood plus a mixture with ecstasy," the doctor described this important case.
"She was at the Holesovice Exhibition Park at a party."
"What is interesting is that it didn't seem strange to the mother that her daughter was absent for 48 hours," said the department director surprised.
It is precisely the disinterest of parents or their unusual tolerance of their rejection of drinking that are the main cause of the development of child alcoholism.
According to experts, however, we are not talking about dependence, in its strict sense, for children.
“Alcoholism refers to a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years with all the phenomena resulting from it, but not found in children.”
“Among those who use acool repeatedly, this is rather a significantly unfavourable socio-family background,” explained the Head of Department Pélikan.
According to the spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunk children were hospitalized this year until mid-November at the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with severe intoxication requiring hospitalization are included in the statistics.
Drunk children who are after emergency care brought home by their parents or by the police are not counted.
In addition to the cases of children who sit down and drink a bottle of alcohol after school, according to Pelikan, there are three seasonal waves with which one can count: the day of witches, St. Sylvester and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink despite bad results or they celebrate the beginning of the holiday."
"Of course I lived on Witch's Day with the admission of seven drunk children at a time," Pelikan said.
The drunk child who spent the night in the hospital in detoxification under medical control is paradoxically in a better position than the one who came home and suffers the next day of the "wood bite".
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and lack of glucose are eliminated by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
“They are better off because they have a great evening and then a gentle awakening and nothing hurts them.”
"They're just amazed at where they're," says Pélikan, knowing that from time to time it ruins the good mood of patients at least with the note to pay for their care.
Transport by ambulance and intensive care bed hospitalization can go up to tens of thousands of crowns.
"Sometimes I applied this as a means of education by telling these children how much their drunkenness cost and that they could spend the whole summer on seasonal work to repay a single evening," Pelikan added.
However, according to him, health insurance companies in their regressive management, which should recover from parents the charges related to care, do not deal with cases of drunk children.
Two L-159s are in foreign hands in Spain for the first time.
Two of the five L-159 aircraft, for which the Ministry of Defense has exchanged transport aircraft Casa C-295M, took off on Tuesday to Seville, Spain, where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is headquartered.
This is the first time that such aircraft become the property of someone other than the Czech army.
However, they were abroad as part of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seat versions of the L-159T1 that were previously in service in the Czech army and were in flight condition.
The remaining Lestrois aircraft are single-seat versions of the L-159.
These are currently stationed at Aéro Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the company Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the Ministry of Defense’s press department, the physical departure of the Vodochody aircraft is currently unknown.
"The L-159 single-seat aircraft planned for the exchange were taken on aircraft stored for a long time without causing any additional charges or investments for the Ministry of Defense."
"The two-seat L-159 T1 were exchanged in the state," Pejsek told Pravo.
He added that the army will not be left without biplaces since the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aéro Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159 monoplaces into two biplaces.
The military took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second scheduled for delivery by the end of this year.
According to Pejsek EADS has committed to introducing the aircraft into the equipment of some Alliance countries.
“In the contract it is clearly stated that the one taking the L-159 aircraft into account is EADS and that they will be used to train pilots from NATO member countries.”
"It is therefore the matter of the one who considers to determine how to this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced, some time ago, that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for SEK 3.5 billion was approved last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Ministry of Defense did not launch a tender and contacted EADS directly.
The defense leadership argued at the time that the exchange ensures future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army has purchased 72 aircraft from Aero Vodochody and uses only 24, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft will likely have legal implications.
The European Commission has, however, filed a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence before the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been selected in a European-wide tender and in no case by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The military has already taken delivery of three Casa aircraft, the latter is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
An index longer than the annular is a sign of low cancer risk
Men who have the index longer than the annular are at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday in the British journal Cancer.
This can depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, for men under the age of 60,” said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Research on Cancer at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should undergo the prostate cancer test, including by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in the UK followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the right hand index shorter than the anular.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, they found the same likelihood of prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the annular, however, the risk fell to 33 percent, for men before the age of 60 the risk decreased to 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two aforementioned fingers – formed during the prenatal period – indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is testosterone that helps in the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of this study but does not seem to him that the relationship between the length of fingers and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
