Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as does support for private enterprises.
Crime has become a greater concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the United States in much of the region.
These are some of the findings of the latest Latinobarometer survey taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it follows the changes in attitude in the region.
Two related elements emerge from the results of this year’s survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the rather sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the South Pacific (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has fallen from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also increased in Mexico, where the economy recovered after experiencing a sharp drop in output last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, lowering the regional average (see Table 2).
About 44% of respondents in the region said they were satisfied with how their country’s democracy worked in practice; this figure is the same as last year but with a sharp increase from 25% in 2001 (Chart 3)
Around 34% said they had confidence in their country’s parliament and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but a sharp increase from 2003 (respective 17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, economic problems in Latin America shaken support for democracy.
If this lasted well during the global financial crisis, it is due to the fact that many countries in America have only experienced a brief recession and benefited from a strong recovery.
In addition, a social security network helped protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again this year to 32%.)
But the mood varies considerably from country to country (cf. Graph 4).
Brazil’s good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a broadly shared sense of progress.
This is rarer in Mexico and Central America where the recession has been more severe and where violent crimes have worsened.
It is only the second time since the poll began that more respondents across Latin America as a whole have cited crime rather than unemployment as the most important problem for their country (see Table 5).
Approximately 31% say they themselves or a loved one have been a victim of a criminal act in the past year; nevertheless, this figure is down from 38% last year and is the lowest since 1995.
More robust economic performance is reflected in increased support for private enterprise and market economy: approximately 71% of respondents in the region say that private enterprise is essential for development, compared to 56% in 2007 (see chart 6).
Some 58% believe that the market economy is the only system that will make their country developed, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela agree with this opinion (and 80% support private enterprise); even though their left-wing president, Hugo Chavez, expropriates many private companies.
Brazil is the largest leader in the region, mentioned by 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, down 11% from last year).
But the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, while Venezuela enjoys this distinction in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
