An arsenic-tolerant microbe raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, expands the field to find new forms of life on Earth and beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacterium here on Earth, they say it shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
“This body has a double capacity.”
"It can grow either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
“That’s why it’s very special, even though it’s far from being a truly ‘foreign’ form of life,” commented Paul Davies C. W. of the Arizona State University, co-author of the report in the online edition of Thursday’s Science journal.
Six major elements have long been considered essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But the researchers found that the bacterium, discovered in Lake Mono, California, is able to continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"We wonder what is still possible," said Ariel Anbar D. of the Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in researching life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, says Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not disclose the details of the discovery, has generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could disclose the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This was not the case.
"The discovery shows that in other planetary environments organisms may be able to use other elements to trigger biochemistry and that the 'standard' set of elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, may not be fixed," said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Institute for Planetary and Space Scientific Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another in fundamental biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It was not a coincidental discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Lake Mono because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, she speculated that a microbe exposed to both substances could be able to replace each other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is really similar to that of phosphorus."
“As a result, organisms find it difficult to distinguish these elements separately.”
"But arsenic is different enough that it doesn't work exactly like phosphorus; it penetrates inside and, somehow, gum the work of our biochemical machine," Anbar explained.
The researchers collected the bacterium known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing has ever shown that this could work.
Arsenic was more common at the beginning of Earth’s existence, she says; thus, the researchers hypothesized that early life forms could have used it.
This suggests that there could be other ways of shaping life, not just the way life on Earth was shaped in the beginning," said Foster, who wasn't part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
