Justice ministry prosecutors have lifted criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, arising from a case related to a former campaign assistant and his efforts to get a lobbying job for the woman's husband, Senator's lawyers announced on Wednesday.
The decision puts an end to the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a potential Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential election until the scandal surrounding his case made national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign’s office said it was “very happy” with the decision, the result of a year-long investigation.
The Senator could still be exposed to disciplinary measures taken by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Ensign’s lawyers said the Justice Department had “informed that Senator Ensign is no longer the subject of the investigation and that he has no intention ofining any charges against him in this case.”
The Ministry of Justice refused to comment on the matter.
The announcement came as a kind of surprise for many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, saying there would be significant evidence that Mr. Ensign had conspired to violate a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
Interviews, emails and other documents, first disclosed in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, get a lucrative lobbying job to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once served as a treasurer during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; according to documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been an employee of Mr. Ensign, he was forbidden by law for a year to lobby his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual deal between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the case, appears to be in conflict with the so-called ban on lobbying.
According to the evidence that has been made public, “there appears to be prima facie evidence of a plot to violate and substantial violation of the rotating door law,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients from a government investigation.
Although the ministry judge refused to explain the reasoning leading to the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the ministry seemed to be cautious about political prosecution after a number of high-level retaliations raised by its public integrity department, including last year’s decisions to abandon prosecution against former senator Ted Stevens accused of failing to prosecute.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take the guns, said Melanie Sloan, the general director of Citizens’ Responsibility and Ethics at Washington, a defence group that has received several complaints against Ensign in the case.
“This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don’t apply to them,” she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's chief attorney, said in an interview that he had received a phone call from a Justice Department prosecutor on Monday and follow-up the next day, telling him the ministry was not seeking charges against his client.
Ensign’s team of lawyers had cooperated with prosecutors to try to convince them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed Wednesday in a statement, “had acted in accordance with the law.”
Mr. Coggins refused to specify the legal arguments he had made to the prosecutor’s office.
“I’m not comfortable entering into the details of my discussions with the Justice Department, except to say we think they made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to abandon an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that Mr. Ensign's parents' payment of $96,000 to Hampton violated federal electoral law.
The election commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a leading Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
