Mr. Ensign also attended a lunch with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and asked the transport secretary to schedule a meeting on behalf of the airline after hiring Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When news of the case emerged last year, Ensign apologized to his voters and resigned from his position as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
Afterining a low profile for several months, Ensign said two weeks ago that he intended to run for a third term in the Senate.
Announcing that Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Justice Department and end its investigation.
Senator Ensign is looking forward to continuing her hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she says.
