Can civilization bring the divisions closer?
After a campaign marked by invectivity and negativity, a minimum of civilisation broke out in Washington this week.
Is this a precursor sign of a real bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders has produced no breakthrough on the major issues to be addressed during the “shallow duck” session.
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two sides as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each camp wanted to score points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit committee was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain among the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide; but which, however, still divides the members.
This is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both sides are now in a period of mutual testing and testing in order to obtain signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That’s why Tuesday’s meeting and subsequent participants’ comments revealed a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxation, expenses, health care or fees, both sides remain miles away.
Nevertheless, the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed on the tone," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethical and Public Policy.
This is inevitable after the elections.
Elections arouse party passions and then they fade away.
It is good.”
On certain issues, including those on the agenda of the "cowed duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and nobody is in favor of it.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve part or all of it, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on extending unemployment benefits, even because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favor of tax cuts for the wealthy, while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
Following Tuesday’s White House meeting, more optimism is expected about a possible agreement on the issues discussed during the session on the “shallow duck”, with the ratification of the “New START” pact.
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the “lame duck” session will not necessarily lead to a better agreement between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, or even inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to real cooperation.
"I consider most of what is happening between today and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present at the tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know they must try to be up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the first reactions to the deficit commission’s recommendations that include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, pushing the retirement age and cutting spending.
Co-Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the toughest tasks in Washington and, according to them, put the issue of deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18 member committee to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have had a hard time reaching that number.
The biggest resistance remains among the group’s elected; which suggests that there is little motivation or willingness to compromise on tax issues, at least today.
Galston planned two phases in the fight between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and healthcare; to be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
The public opinion.
It is widely proven that, despite the party spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to an impasse, as in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the public.
Those who are judged to be losers will have to change their course and find compromises.
However, this would be an optimistic viewpoint.
Partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans in Congress than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
Meanwhile, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more consistent election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilisation exposed this week may be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a ground of agreement on the issues that still divide them.
