Faced with this evolution of the situation, anxiety has risen among the former Khmer Rouge fighters of Anlong Veng; complicating their efforts to reconcile and their willingness to re-integrate into Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything,” said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Centre, an independent body that conducts research on the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
“The situation creates divisions within families.”
Under the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia from 1975 to 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, illness or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-United government in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There, they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last of the movements surrendered in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary were leading the guerrilla from their base in the mountains of western Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a sequel to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to defect from the government, culminating in the surrender of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had held the head, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 while awaiting his trial.
Without their benefactors, most of the former Khmer Rouge fighters have sunk into the black misery common to rural areas of Cambodia; and many are those who remain nostalgic of the movement.
Although some elite Khmer Rouge officers have retained their positions as local leaders in exchange for depositing arms, they are low-grade and unskilled farmers.
“These people benefited from very little follow-up after the surrender,” said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which hosts public forums across Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
“They are immersed in the agraric utopian ideology of the regime.”
“They were raised in an environment where doing business is a foreign concept.”
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as a poor rice farmer.
“Life under the Khmer Rouge was good,” he said.
“Ta Mok feeds everybody.”
But now life is difficult because we have to provide for our own needs.”
