The court’s mandate is to judge senior executives and the main perpetrators of crimes but it did not say whether it was proceeding beyond these four cases.
More would be needed to calm the fears at Anlong Veng.
The latest media speculation has turned to Im Chaem, 64, a former district head in Banteay Meanchey province under the Khmer Rouge in the 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodian Documentation Center that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project where thousands of forced laborers were believed to have died.
Recently, on a thirsty evening, Im Chaem was returning from work to the field near his wooden house on pilotis, on a road outside Anlong Veng.
