“Reconciliation in Khmer terms is to reconnect the broken pieces,” he says.
"We have to put these pieces together so that we can understand."
The center produced the first government-approved manual on the Khmer Rouge, "A 75-page history of Democratic Kampuchea."
He distributed it to Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education’s history textbooks, designed for higher schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, young people in Anlong Veng know only a few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city’s ties to the regime.
