Zapatero and German Red Line
Berlin has chosen to stay in the euro, but it has set the conditions for the entire Union.
Market tensions have triggered a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero announced new methods of adjustment, ranging from tax cuts for SMEs, regulation of private placement agencies or removal of the 426 euros of unemployment aid without professional contribution to the privatization of 49% of AENA, the management of the airports of Barajas and El Prat and 30% of the State Lotteries.
On the other hand, Vice-President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, joins with Chancellor Angela Merkel’s criticism of her responsibility for unleashing the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
It should be noted that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another constraint of the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which shocks with that ofining the old traditions of most of its partners.
Faced with European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, integrated by itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, and the south would leave the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the Mark, although now it seems like science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, almost 50% of the population.
The third, a new design of the euro, in line with German proposals for greater macro-economic control, fiscal rigour, fines to countries that violate them, possible suspension of payments from one of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, therefore now there is no room for excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were boosting deficits, the German government invented a constitutional reform to prevent them from starting in 2016.
This was the first sign of discrepancy between what Germany thought it should be done (tax rigour plans and public finance stability) and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second blow of the Central European country was when Merkel hardly extended the decision to save Greece.
Since then it has been the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion and the public were against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expressed a clear position, calling for the reform of the EU treaties to make it possible to rescue a country and at the same time compel private lenders to bear a part of the cost.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it hastened the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, though slightly sweetened, was approved and, in the following months, we should witness the process of reforming the Union that makes these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not want to cross.
And it tells us all that even if we must now take measures with which we may not agree too much, from that date the old functioning of the euro would have ended.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries that break the rules will be severely punished, they may be forced to declare payment cessation and, in that case, the private sector will also bear a part of the costs.
Germany signals us that we must follow a tough growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, like the one that presided over Spanish growth in the years of the boom, will simply not be tolerated.
The set is clear.
It would be bad not to hear it.
It is not just about bringing the government deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we are asking is much harder.
And what he should absolutely not do under these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give us a greater tranquility.
Let us take advantage of the opportunity that we have been given until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also heard it in this form and his double statement (the reforms promised after last Saturday's meeting with big companies and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel's criticism, the way has been paved for the thesis that order must be put at home.
But the red line Germany has drawn is there, and they don’t seem to move it.
And among the possibilities that are being considered, one cannot rule out the possibility of leaving a monetary zone too crowded with unserious countries.
And in that case, Germany will always be able to tell us that it has warned us.
Sport and law fraud
The tricks similar to those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the willingness to escape a penalty.
The expulsion in principle by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has shed a lot of ink on the anti-sports character of such behavior and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, a few minutes before the end of the match (that their team already clearly won), both players deliberately wasted time when they made mistakes in determining the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and given that Real Madrid will end up being the leader of its group, the two players will fulfill the regulatory penalty during the next match of the dam match against Auxerre and can pass without cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee sanctioned the team’s coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and various financial sums to the players involved.
Provoking a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the rules not written, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that appeared in the case is due to the fact that this had as the protagonist a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem displays nobility and honor and which in past occasions sentenced its players to a fine for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho, which adds an additional episode to his extended history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behavior not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, if with these actions a fraud of law is committed; because, in fact, they are actions respecting the sports regulation, but seem to circumvent its meaning.
The question is to look at the type of harm they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that includes the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opponent players, an aspect that with these actions was not endangered, i.e. there was no violent play.
Another of those assets that is referred to with correct play is to prevent the team of offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not conform to what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, since its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the penalty, but their action was precisely trying to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalization of the referee.
They waited and they gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is the type of benefit that offenders get from the deliberate misconduct examined.
Here it seems necessary to see that one does not put in a situation of disadvantage to the rival and one does not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the outcome of the action implies the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And that’s not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn’t rely on those players.
Obviously the advantage is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without any cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of uncertainty, as the team could be eliminated all of a sudden and apart from that, with this action the players perform a penalty match and move to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, climbing the ladder, it’s not so clear that this is an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to the sporting spirit, which is still part of making strategic decisions that promote the maximum profit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the penalty (this would indeed be a clear case of law fraud), otherwise they chose rather the time when they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding the penalty or escaping it.
Even though the boundary between genius and law fraud is diffuse, in this occasion I think we have had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises due to two factors: because there were two self-expulsions and because of the way to pass the director to provoke them.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
