The peculiarity of Pakistan’s nuclear program – the fact that weapons are not assembled, but are stored in components to make it difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack – is one of the main reasons for concern in Washington.
This is what Ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, lists in a report before the visit of former National Security Advisor James Jones: "The proximity of certain nuclear installations in the Taliban-attacked territory, the dispersal of nuclear materials whose noise is low and the vulnerability of the transport of nuclear materials."
