“Pakistan has had to hire staff with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the decline in educational and cultural levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people who work in nuclear or missile programs,” Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev said during a meeting with U.S. counterparts.
The new in the documentation filtered by Julian Assange’s portal is the increasingly reduced cooperation between the United States and Pakistan in the field of nuclear proliferation and the high degree of Pakistani nuclear weapons production.
A mail from the Embassy in May, which described the communication with Pakistan as “frustrating,” argued: “Transparency is often non-existent; aid offers remain unanswered or are removed.”
In another message, Peter Lavoy, a National Intelligence official for South Asia, notes that “despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan produces nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world.”
Ambassador Patterson also asked Washington, during a visit by the army chief, General Ashfaq Kayani, to make it clear to the official that "the Pakistani army must end its tacit support for terrorist groups."
