EU changes rules for obtaining visas
Individuals must go to the Visa Applicant Service Center before their interview in the Consular Section; the cost the waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to appear at the Visa Applicant Service Centers (ASC) before interviewing at the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take the applicant’s biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will have a number of advantages for applicants, among which are the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, there will no longer be a need to make a payment to get an appointment, another payment for processing the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The applicant will make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa with application (this includes visas for temporary workers) and $390 for business and investor visas.
Persons wishing to renew their visa will not have to attend an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only appear at the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken in the AUC, applicants who want a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will stay there less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For more information about the new procedure for applying for the visa, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
