A global plan to renew lighting
The United Nations has proposed a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHGs) equivalent to one-third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan follows the major concrete projects that the UN hopes to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan filed yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluorocompact bulbs or, better, by diode-electroluminescent bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), the majority of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of greenhouse gas emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That’s the equivalent of 70% of the global car fleet’s emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitter countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should boost global greenhouse gas emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract from this balance sheet another 5 Gt to stabilize the climate rise to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, or 5%, is produced by light.
With compact fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by twice.
A fluorescent light bulb lasts an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by manufacturer Philips this week – this company has also participated in the UN study – have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, giving an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These all-new bulbs can also work with rhostats in addition to emitting very little heat.
They do not contain mercury.
Several specialists have raised concerns about compact fluorescent bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers put in place instructions.
But, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluorocompact bulb, but rather coal-fired thermal plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce wasted electricity in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains each country would make through this international program.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, or the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost it $2.5 billion.
