Unemployment remained stable in France in the third quarter
The unemployment rate in France according to the International Bureau of Labour (BIT) remained stable at 9.3% in the metropolises (9.7% counting overseas departments), according to the corrected data of seasonal variations (CVS) published on Thursday by the Insee.
The number of unemployed in the metropolitan area is 2,631 million.
The second quarter data was confirmed for 9.3% of the working population in the metropolis and 9.7% with DOMs.
Over the course of a year, the unemployment rate has risen by 0.1 points.
More broadly, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France were not working in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether or not they were available within two weeks to work and whether or not they were looking for a job.
The situation of young people present on the labour market has further deteriorated, with a further rise in the unemployment rate, rising to 24.2% in the metropolis (+0.9 points over three months, +0.5 points over one year) and 25% including DOMs.
In the third quarter, 637 000 young people aged 15 to 24 were unemployed within the meaning of the BIT.
The elderly experienced a slight increase in unemployment, to 6.4% in the metropolis (+0.2 points over three months as well as over a year), or 482,000 people 50 years or older, and 6.6% with DOMs.
Only the 25-49 years old benefited from a stability of unemployment in the third quarter, at 8.3% in the metropolis (-0.1 point over three months, +0.1 point over a year) and 8.8% across France.
Insee has not published monthly unemployment rates since 2006, after a controversy over its method of calculation.
Eurostat, the statistical agency of the European Union, on the other hand, continues to do so and announced on Tuesday a rate of 9.8% for France (DOM included) in October after 9.9% in September.
