Hackers and spies in diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it turns out to be an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs the relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and prefigures a future dominated by regression.
Let us proceed by order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that every file made up by a secret service (of any nation) consists exclusively of press cuts.
The “extraordinary” American revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those Berlusconi owns), and Gaddafi’s sinisterly caricatural profile has long been for cabaret artists to sketch.
The rule that secret records should only be compiled from already known news is essential to the dynamics of the intelligence services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the previous works.
And this is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unprecedented research (neither does he know where to look for news on the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism only believe what they already know, and which reaffirms what they had already learned.
This is the success mechanism of Dan Brown.
I go for the secret records.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or of limited mind) the head of the secret services (otherwise he could be, what I know, editor at Libération), who only holds as true what he recognizes.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. embassy in Rome was sending to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every cultivated person already knows, namely, that embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since heads of state can call or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises of representation, have turned into centers of espionage.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy under a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the world’s most powerful country is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal does not put the victims in crisis so much as the “bulls.”
But let’s get back to the profound nature of what happened.
Once, in Orwell’s time, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy had been fully fulfilled since, being able to control every movement through the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway taken and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as it happens now, that even the crypt of power secrets cannot escape a hacker’s control, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets stand?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that knowing anything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, because it belongs to the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means taking away all power from her.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to put any reserved information online – it would be like publishing it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it’s just as obvious that with current technologies, it’s futile to hope to be able to maintain confidential reports over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How will private and reserved relationships beined in the future?
I know well that, for now, my prediction is science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am forced to imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligences to uncontrollable routes, bearing only messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the rare information written in the heels of a shoe.
The information will be stored in a single copy in locked boxes: in the bottom, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I have had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving forward in crab, that is, backwards.
A century after wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet reestablished a wireless telegraph (telephony).
Video cassettes (analog) had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going forward and back and discovering all the secrets of editing, while now CDs (digital) only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, that is, by macro proportions.
With high-speed trains, you get from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the travel it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not surprising that politics and communications technologies come back to horseback cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was hidden in the secrets of the embassies.
Now it is the embassies that are asking for confidential information from the press.
Climate Change: How France Fails to Make Funding Promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine compliance with the promises of rapidly unlocked financing (so-called early start financing) made by developed countries.
And the French bulldozers are revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has pledged €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (i.e. €420 million per year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU played the big game to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast-start funding: report detailing the actions of its Member States, press conference, large side event, distribution of brochures...
Transparency is appreciated and appreciated for its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announced that it had allocated €2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must, according to the Copenhagen Agreement, be "new and additional", in order to ensure that additional effort is made without being at the expense of public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what “new and additional” means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has considered 2009 as the reference year: international funding isined, and it is adding 150 million over three years under fast-start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of public development aid.
On the contrary, France estimates that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous years or to the overall level of public development aid.
Concretely, the total amount of France’s support to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to meet its commitment in terms of “new and additional” funding.
Another important factor is the distribution between donations and loans.
There are no rules and everyone chooses their own method.
Some, like France, consider that 1 euro borrowed equals 1 euro given.
Obviously, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions that rely on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At most, only the cost of the loan for the lender country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be counted under its commitments.
But France has nothing to do with such a reasoning: it "respects" its 420 million euro commitment by making 91,5% of loans (389,8 million euros) and 8,5% of donations (36,1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the EU that uses such a massive amount of loan.
Germany requires 46 percent, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (in other countries) comply with their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the very vast majority of the European Union puts 1 € to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Lovely tour of pass!
In short, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only €36.1 million, she comes to believe that she is spending €420 million “new and additional” in line with her promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would other member states continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since developing countries are not completely fooled...
The early financing chapter is just a small, relatively short-term issue compared to the whole of the climate discussions.
But it could be another grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its accounting mode for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with other European Union countries.
But above all, France could advance discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or how loans are accounted for.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope therefore rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s fast start and its vision of “additionality” and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to advance the discussions.
Pesticides injected by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published on Wednesday by the association Future Generations (ex-Movement for Rights and Respect for Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results “do not have statistically significant value in view of the low number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated”, bought between July and September the foods generally consumed in four meals and one bite in a day by a ten-year-old child, in the supermarkets of Oise and Paris.
These types of meals, including official recommendations – five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day – as well as sweets, have been examined by laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance sheet is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens, and five are classified as certain carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors, according to studies from several institutions such as the International Centre for Research on Cancer.
“Even if, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, it is clear in our investigation that the reality of consumers’ exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and/or PE is worrying,” the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three proven certain carcinogens as well as twenty residues likely to disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, which was planned to be used in the study, contains traces of six chemicals, one of which is a fungicide banned in France.
The same goes for Kenya’s green beans, included in lunch, on which the study detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
Furthermore, the steak, the tuna in the box, and even the bag of bread and chewing gum were filled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the most “rich” with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not exempt.
The final risk for the consumer of this “contaminant cocktail” is “probably underestimated,” according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, proposed "in the face of the urgency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the rise of civilization diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) found residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
